This was usually done by sending it to a friend with an epistle prefixed, in which the author went through the polite farce1 of inviting the recipient to correct its faults and so let it live, or to suppress it altogether (Ludus i. 1-4, 13-18).

Ausonius sometimes revised‚ supplemented, and reissued poems already published, usually (but not always) adding a new dedication. Thus the Techno- paegnion, originally dedicated to Paulinus, underwent some alterations and additions before being re- published with its new dedication to Pacatus; but in the second edition of the Fasti the prefatory poem, originally addressed to Hesperius, was merely adapted by slight verbal alterations to suit Gregorius.
